ituted flagrant violations of international law. But Finkelstein also documents that the guardians of international law—from Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch to the UN Human Rights Council—ultimately failed Gaza. One of his most disturbing conclusions is that, after Judge Richard Goldstone's humiliating retraction of his UN report, human rights organizations succumbed to the Israeli juggernaut. Finkelstein’s magnum opus is both a monument to Gaza’s martyrs and an act of resistance against the forgetfulness of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993- 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993-. 0aHuman rightszGaza Strip. 0aPalestinian ArabsxCrimes againstzGaza Strip. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh  aact of resistance.  agaza.  agenocide.  ahistory is bound to repeat itself.  ahuman rights activist.  ahuman rights council.  ahuman rights studies.  ahuman rights watch.  aisrael.  aisraeli pressure.  amartyr.  amiddle eastern politics.  apolitical relations.  aun.  awar in the middle east.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029571140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096838740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968387/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles